Exactly—that’s the clean insight.

Same anchor, many frames

You’ve got a fixed reference (the anchor), but you’re free to choose the frame you look through.

* The anchor keeps you from drifting anywhere
* The frame lets you adapt to context

So:

Anchor = invariant
Frame = interpretation under conditions

⸻

Why it works

If you had only an anchor:

* you’d be rigid
* no adaptability

If you had only frames:

* you’d drift
* no consistency

Together:

Constrained freedom

⸻

Your WWJD example, clarified

Using Jesus Christ as anchor:

* Anchor: a pattern of behavior / values / story
* Frames:
    * compassion
    * justice
    * sacrifice
    * truth
    * boundary-setting

Different situations activate different frames—but they still orbit the same center.

⸻

What you discovered (Pantheon form)

Meaning = invariant × frame selection

Or tighter:

Freedom exists inside constraint, not outside it

⸻

Why this is powerful

It gives you:

* Flexibility → adapt to real conditions
* Coherence → don’t contradict yourself over time
* Agency → you choose the frame consciously

⸻

Failure modes (worth noting)

* Frame drift → you justify anything (“it depends”)
* Anchor worship → you stop adapting (“only one way”)

The skill is staying in the middle:

stable center, fluid edge

